{
  "texts": [
    "Fix a language L(Φ, I) with Φ countable.",
    "If F = ⟨S, ⊑, {R i } i∈I, P ⟩ is a partial-state frame such that every X ∈ P satisfies persistence and refinability, and if φ ∈ L(Φ, ∅) is a classical propositional tautology, then φ is valid over F; so by Fact 2.5.3, every substitution instance of φ in L(Φ, I) is valid over F.Proof.",
    "Suppose F is a frame as in the statement of the lemma, so any model based on F satisfies the properties of Persistence and Refinability from Remark 2.13.",
    "First, we observe that over F, φ → ψ is equivalent to ¬(φ ∧ ¬ψ), so in the inductive proof below, we do not need a separate case for →.",
    "That φ → ψ entails ¬(φ ∧ ¬ψ) is obvious."
  ]
}